# KidsLearnAI Year 2 Curriculum

## 8-Term AI-Ready Program for Ages 11-13

_Empowering the Next Generation with AI Education_

---

## Curriculum Philosophy

### Designed for 11-13 Year Olds

This curriculum recognizes that 11-13 year olds are ready for more abstract thinking and complex projects. They can handle:

- **Faster pacing** — concepts can be covered more quickly with less repetition
- **Abstract concepts** — functions with parameters/returns, data structures
- **Longer projects** — multi-feature applications that span multiple sessions
- **Independent problem-solving** — less hand-holding, more exploration
- **Real-world applications** — projects that feel "useful" and professional

### What This Curriculum Includes

| Concept | Why It Works for 11-13 |
|---------|------------------------|
| Functions with parameters/returns | They can understand "input → process → output" |
| Dictionaries | Key-value pairs make sense with real examples |
| File I/O (reading/writing) | Straightforward with good scaffolding |
| API calls | Using pre-built AI tools is accessible and impressive |
| Data visualization | Creating charts from data is achievable |
| AI concepts (deep understanding) | Conceptual understanding + practical application |

### What We DON'T Include (Still Too Advanced)

| Concept | Why We Skip It |
|---------|----------------|
| Pandas (full library) | Complex syntax, confusing error messages |
| Building ML models from scratch | Even with scikit-learn, abstraction is too high |
| Neural networks | Way beyond this age group |
| Computer vision libraries (OpenCV) | Adult developer tools |
| NLP libraries (NLTK, spaCy) | Steep learning curves |

### The "AI-Ready" Philosophy

Instead of pretending 11-13 year olds can build production AI systems, we focus on:

1. **Strong Python skills** that ARE prerequisites for future AI work
2. **Deep AI literacy** — understanding how AI actually works
3. **Using AI tools** — interacting with AI APIs rather than building models
4. **Data thinking** — understanding how data drives AI decisions
5. **Ethical awareness** — understanding bias, privacy, and responsible AI use

